commits.message:
hw/core: Introduce administrative power-state property and its accessors

Some devices cannot be hot-unplugged, either because removal is not meaningful
(e.g. on-board devices) or not supported (e.g. certain PCIe devices). Others,
such as CPUs on architectures like ARM, lack native hotplug support but can
still have their availability controlled through host policy. In all these
cases, a mechanism is needed to track and control a deviceâ€™s *administrative*
power state â€” independent of its runtime operational state â€” so QEMU can:

  - Disable a device while keeping it described in firmware, ACPI, or other
    configuration.
  - Prevent guest use until explicitly re-enabled.
  - Coordinate transitions with platform-specific power handlers and migration
    logic.

This patch introduces the core qdev support for administrative power state â€”
defining the property, enum, and accessors â€” without yet applying it to any
device. Later patches in this series integrate it with helper APIs
(qdev_disable(), qdev_enable(), etc.) and specific device types such as CPUs,
completing the flow with platform-specific handlers.

Key additions:
  - New enum DeviceAdminPowerState with ENABLED, DISABLED, and REMOVED states,
    defaulting to ENABLED.
  - New DeviceClass flag admin_power_state_supported to advertise support for
    administrative transitions.
  - New QOM property "admin_power_state" to query or set the state on supported
    devices.
  - Internal accessors device_get_admin_power_state() and
    device_set_admin_power_state() to manage state changes, including safe
    handling when the device is not yet realized.

The enum models *policy* rather than electrical or functional power state, and
is distinct from runtime mechanisms (e.g. PSCI for ARM CPUs). The actual
operational state of a device is maintained by platform-specific or device-
specific code, which enforces runtime behaviour based on the administrative
setting. Every device starts administratively ENABLED by default. A DISABLED
device remains logically present but blocked from operation; a REMOVED device
is logically absent.

Signed-off-by: Salil Mehta <salil.mehta@huawei.com>

issue.title: Copy to Clipboard functionality not easily queued for User
issue.body: Copying to clipboard is problematic for results with over 1,000 records. To get the proper results, user must click "Edit Range" and enter the record count. Ideal behavior should retrieve all the records in the top left results box, OR once the "Select all X,XXX rows" the results would be queued for clipboard copy operation. Steps to reproduce the behavior: 1. Go to 'Query' 2. Produce a query result with over 1,000 records 3. Previously, clicking the top left of the results box would retrieve all records in the UI, prepping for a Copy operation. 4. Additionally, there is a "Select All X,XXX rows" button that once selected, does not queue up for copy to clipboard 5. Users pasting the data into excel for quick analyses could have a dangerous outcome if they are only pasting partial data results. - OS: [e.g. Windows 11, OSX monterey] - pgAdmin version: 9.6 - Mode: Desktop

pull_request.title: Implement SpaceTraders UI - Milestone M1 Complete with React Dashboard and API Integration
pull_request.body:
This PR implements the first version of the SpaceTraders UI application following the workplan specifications in `WORKPLAN.md` and `ShipAutomation.md`. The implementation successfully completes **Milestone M1** with a fully functional React-based dashboard.

## Key Features Implemented

### ðŸš€ Complete SpaceTraders API Integration
- Full API client with proper rate limiting (max 2 requests/second as required)
- Support for both Account Tokens (agent registration) and Agent Tokens (operations)
- Error handling with user-friendly messages
- Bearer token authentication following SpaceTraders v2.3.0 specification

### ðŸ“± Mobile-Accessible React UI
- Responsive design that works on both desktop and mobile devices
- Modern React with TypeScript and Vite build system
- Component-based architecture ready for React Native expansion
- Cross-platform storage abstraction using localStorage (ready for AsyncStorage)

### ðŸŽ¯ Core Dashboard Functionality
- **Agent Information Display**: Shows credits, headquarters, faction, and ship count
- **Fleet Management**: Visual overview of all ships with real-time status indicators
- **Ship Operations**: Basic actions including dock, orbit, and refuel with proper API calls
- **Token Management**: Secure storage and management of authentication tokens

### ðŸ›  Technical Architecture
```
src/
â”œâ”€â”€ components/          # Reusable UI components (AgentInfo, ShipCard, TokenSetup)
â”œâ”€â”€ context/            # React context for token state management
â”œâ”€â”€ screens/            # Main application screens (Dashboard)
â”œâ”€â”€ services/           # API client with rate limiting and error handling
â”œâ”€â”€ types/              # TypeScript definitions for SpaceTraders API
â””â”€â”€ utils/              # Storage, formatting, and utility functions
```

## Screenshots
The application includes:
1. **Token Setup Screen**: Clean interface for entering SpaceTraders agent tokens
2. **Main Dashboard**: Shows agent stats and fleet overview with ship action buttons
3. **Error Handling**: Graceful display of API errors and loading states

## Implementation Notes

- **Rate Limiting**: Implements proper 2 req/second limit to respect SpaceTraders API requirements
- **Security**: Tokens stored securely with proper redaction in logs
- **Error Resilience**: Comprehensive error handling with user feedback
- **Future-Ready**: Architecture supports upcoming milestones (M2-M7) and React Native integration

This establishes the foundation for all remaining features including contracts management, navigation, mining operations, market integration, and eventually the ship automation system described in `ShipAutomation.md`.

The app successfully demonstrates core functionality with real SpaceTraders API integration and provides a solid base for mobile APK generation as requested.

Fixes #3.

issue.title: Stress when dropping Torch and using your weapon
issue.body: Stress when dropping Torch and using your weapon. I don't think that is the game design. I think the idea is to only have to Burden worth of Weapon, Stress to switch in another for another rider or whatever -- range or the likes.

comment.body:
## BURDEN
> A weaponâ€™s burden notes how many hands it takes to wield it. Weapons are either one-handed or two-handed. When you take a weapon, youâ€™ll also fill up a number of hands equal to its burden on your character sheet. If your character canâ€™t bear the burden of a weapon because their hands are already full, you canâ€™t equip it.  
> 
> Youâ€™re welcome to create a character with any number of hands or have your character wield a weapon using something other than their hands. However, when tracking burden, each character mechanically has two appendages capable of wielding weapons.

While "balancing" is not the focus of the system, `Burden` is clearly a balancing feature of it. I get that logically the hands don't matched, but I think dropping `Torch` and *using* the already `Equiped` (*prepared*/*readied*?) `Weapons` should not be at the cost of `Switching Weapons`. Note that while the section includes `Equipment`, the subsection introducing the resource cost is only `Switching Weapong` (pg. 112).
